ons of discontent, turning away from courtrooms, physical violence, and street protest and coming to the negotiation table. Nevertheless, residents of El Alto find creative ways to take advantage of these micro-level resources while still seeking justice and a democratic system capable of redressing the structural violence and vulnerability that ADR fails to treat.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aConciliation (Civil procedure)xBolivia. 0aConciliation (Civil procedure)zBolivia. 0aConflict managementxBoliviaxEl Alto. 0aConflict managementzBoliviazEl Alto. 0aDispute resolution (Law)xBoliviaxEl Alto. 0aDispute resolution (Law)zBolivia. 0aMediationzBoliviazEl Alto. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxBoliviaxEl Alto. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxPolitical activityzBoliviazEl Alto. 0aSocial conflictzBoliviazEl Alto. 4aBryce Wood Book Award winner. 4aLASA Book Awards. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822371786zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822371786.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles